07354nam a22015015i 9780691252735DE-B159720240307104700.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240307t20231990nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912527357 a10.1515/97806912527352doi  a(DE-B1597)666261  a(OCoLC)1408682605  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aBR238b.P44 2011eb 7aART0150702bisacsh04a246/.53090212221 aPelikan, Jaroslav, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aImago Dei :bThe Byzantine Apologia for Icons /cJaroslav Pelikan. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2023] 4c©1990  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b50 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe A. W. Mellon Lectures in the Fine Arts ;v3500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tIllustrations -- tAbbreviations -- tINTRODUCTION. The Idea in the Image -- tCHAPTER ONE. THE CONTEXT -- tCHAPTER TWO. GRAVEN IMAGES -- tCHAPTER THREE. DIVINITY MADE HUMAN -- tCHAPTER FOUR. THE SENSES SANCTIFIED -- tCHAPTER FIVE HUMANITY. MADE DIVINE -- tCHAPTER SIX. THE GREAT CHAIN OF IMAGES -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA sweeping account of the controversies surrounding the worship of images in the early Byzantine churchIn 726, the Byzantine emperor, Leo III, issued an edict that all religious images in the empire were to be destroyed, a directive that was later endorsed by a synod of the church in 753 under his son, Constantine V. If the policy of Iconoclasm had succeeded, the entire history of Christian art—and of the Christian church, at least in the East—would have been altered.Iconoclasm was defeated by Byzantine politics, popular revolts, monastic piety, and, most fundamentally of all, by theology, just as it had been theology that the opponents of images had used to justify their actions. Analyzing an intriguing chapter in the history of ideas, the renowned scholar Jaroslav Pelikan shows how a faith that began by attacking the worship of images ended first in permitting and then in commanding it.Pelikan charts the theological defense of icons during the iconoclastic controversies of the eighth and ninth centuries, whose high point came in 787, when the Second Council of Nicaea restored the cult of images in the church. He demonstrates how the dogmas of the Trinity and the Incarnation eventually provided the basic rationale for images: because the invisible God had become human and therefore personally visible in Jesus Christ, it became permissible to make images of that Image. And because not only the human nature of Christ, but that of his Mother had been transformed by the Incarnation, she, too, could be “iconized,” together with all the other saints and angels.The iconographic “text” of the book is provided by one of the very few surviving icons from the period before Iconoclasm, the Egyptian tapestry Icon of the Virgin now in the Cleveland Museum of Art. Other icons serve to illustrate the theological argument, just as the theological argument serves to explain the icons.In an incisive foreword, Judith Herrin explains the enduring importance of the book and discusses how later scholars have built on Pelikan’s work.Please note: All images in this ebook are presented in black and white and have been reduced in size.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aIconoclasm. 0aIconsxCultxHistory of doctrinesyEarly church, ca. 30-600. 0aIconsxCultxHistory of doctrinesyMiddle Ages, 600-1500. 0aIconsxCultzByzantine Empire. 7aART / History / Medieval.2bisacsh  a750s.  aAmerican Academy of Political and Social Science.  aApse.  aArius.  aAthanasius of Alexandria.  aByzantine Empire.  aByzantine Iconoclasm.  aCaliph